He acted in this capacity from 1605 up to his death in 1608. His appointment to this post testifies to the high esteem in which he was held as a jurist and to the reputation throughout the world which his writings on international law had brought him. Perhaps the opinion whicb he rendered to the English court in the case ol the Ambassador Mendoza also made the King of Spain look with lavor on his appointment. Mendoza had been involved in the Throgmorton plot directed against Queen Elizabeth, and inquiry was made of Gentili if he could be sentenced to death in England. Although public feeling ran high, and although many men would have yielded to the popular demand lor the exemplary punishment of an ambassador who had violated the elementary principles of hos· pitality in supporting the plot ol assassins and revolutionists, he bravely replied that no other aetion could be taken against Mendoza than dismissal from England.
